alism’English-language translations of previously untranslated essays and interviewsProvides further insight into the thinker’s biographyContributes significantly to our understanding of Derrida’s work in politics, literary theory and philosophyIn two volumes, Geoffrey Bennington and Kas Saghafi present the majority of Jacques Derrida’s untranslated, and previously uncollected, essays and interviews. Dating mostly from 1992 to 2004, these writings offer a fuller picture of Derrida’s biography, theoretical engagements and the stakes of his social and political investments. In the interviews in Essays, Interviews, and Interventions by Jacques Derrida: Thinking What Comes, Volume 1, Derrida proposes the foundation of a new European political culture, discusses the strengths of Nelson Mandela, and reflects on the archive. He also considers his experience of political life, his relationship to institutions (particularly the Collège international de philosophie), and his views on ‘intellectualism’. Whether writing about public health, Palestine, or the notion of the promise, Derrida is razor-sharp and impassioned. These volumes allow significant insight into his mature thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aBennington, Geoffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcQuillan, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaghafi, Kas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079765740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147441071740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474410717423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/